==Old English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[ƿord]]

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|gem-pro|ang}} {{recons|wurdan|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|ang}} {{recons|werdʰo-||word|lang=ine-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|ang}} {{recons|wer-||speak|lang=ine-pro}}; cognate with Old Frisian {{term||word}}, Old Saxon {{term|word
lang=osx}}, Old Dutch {{term|wort}} (Dutch {{term|woord|lang=nl}}), Old High German {{term|wort|lang=goh}} (German {{term|Wort}}), Old Norse {{term|orð}} (Icelandic {{term|orð|lang=is}}, Swedish {{term|ord|lang=sv}}), Gothic {{term|sc=Goth|𐍅𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌳|tr=waurd}}. The Proto-Indo-European root is also the source of Latin {{term|verbum}}, Lithuanian {{term|vardas}}, and, more distantly, of Ancient Greek {{term|sc=polytonic|εἴρω|tr=eirō||I say}} and Old Slavonic {{term||rotiti sę|to swear}} (Russian {{term|sc=Cyrl|ротиться|tr=rotit’cja||to vow}}).

